A coalition of northern civil society groups has called on politicians from the north to convert their campaign and constituency offices to temporary cyber cafes to improve the chances of youths from the region for enrolment into the federal government’s N-Power programme. The call, according to the group, became necessary to help more young people have access to the internet due to paucity of funds. Reading the press statement before newsmen yesterday in Kaduna, Northern Anti-Corruption Front President Yusuf Idris Amoke, also called on regional youths to enrol in the batch ‘C’ of the programme under the Ministry of Humanitarian Affairs, Disaster Management and Social Development. Dear our valued reader, we would like to hear your view about a membership club that we plan to launch. Kindly help us fill this survey. Buhari is now a warehouse for corrupt politicians – Rep candidate PDP chair: Northern elders knock out S/South aspirants 2023 Presidency: We’ll vote for only northern candidate irrespective of political party – Ag ACF chairman